First time offenders of driving under the influence of cannabis will no longer have their driver's license revoked, a federal court in Leipzig ruled on Tuesday. Instead, driver's license authorities must first declare with a medical evaluation whether or not the cannabis user was fit to drive. Read more: 5 facts about cannabis laws in Germany Under current law, a drivers license can be revoked if the driver is unable to drive due to the consumption of alcohol, cannabis or other drugs. In regards to cannabis, the law applied drivers caught with one nanogram per millimeter of tetrahydrocannabinol (THC) — the principal psychoactive constituent of cannabis — in their bloodstream. In 2015, a group of experts proposed the limit of three nanograms per millimeter instead, arguing that a person can still have THC in the bloodstream days after consuming cannabis. However, the Leipzig Federal Administrative Court ruled that the strict limit should remain the same. Send  Facebook   Twitter   google+   Whatsapp   Tumblr   linkedin   stumble   Digg   reddit   Newsvine Permalink https://p.dw.com/p/3FKLW dv/aw (AFP, epd) Every evening, DW's editors send out a selection of the day's hard news and quality feature journalism. You can sign up to receive it directly here.